    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Dorsally flattened with eight smallshell plates articulating dorsally, surrounded by a very wide,soft fleshy girdle. Girdle further broadening to the front, covered with hairs, scales and minute tufts visible under high magnifications and otherwise appears naked. Texture of shell with convex, raised granules and slight growth-lines. When turned over, gills extend halfway to the anus. The articulamentum is thin with small anterior extensions widely separated. Colour variably brown/yellow or pink/orange, mottled white and red. Subtriangular shell-plates with light central stripe.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_6135",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Large, typically around 20-40 mm total body length.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_6136",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Possibly in New Caledonia (unconfirmed), Philippines and Central West Africa, as well as South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Hout Bay to East London.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_6137",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Found in the subtidal zone on rocks and reef platforms.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_6138",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>The only carnivorous chiton genus in South Africa, feeding on mobile invertebrates such as small crustaceans. Waiting for the right moment to strike the widened girdle is lifted up, then folded over to trap the prey underneath.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_6139",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>External fertilization, pelagic trochophore larvae metamorphizes and settles as juvenile chiton.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_6140",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>One of three South African species in this genus but the only one in the Western Cape. The group is still under taxonomic consideration regarding species delineation.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_6141",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
